<section xml:id="sec-dilations-Cartesian" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Transformations that Scale</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
        In this section, we explore a type of transformation which changes the distance 
        between points. Before introducing some examples on the Cartesian <m>x,y</m>-plane,
        we review how the Pythagorean Theorem is used to compute distance between points. 
    </p>
    <!--<sidebyside widths="50% 45%">-->
        <p>
            To compute the length of a segment on a graph we use the Pythagorean 
            Theorem. In <xref ref="diag-seg-measure"/>, the coordinates of point <m>A</m> 
            are <m>(6,6)</m> and of point <m>B</m> are <m>(9,2)</m>. We think of the segment 
            <m>\overline{AB}</m> as the hypotenuse of a triangle with a right angle at
            <m>C=(6,2)</m>. The length of the horizontal leg is found by
            subtracting the <m>x</m>-coordinates, <m>m(\overline{BC})=9-6 = 3</m>, 
            and the vertical distance by subtracting the <m>y</m>-coordinates, 
            <m>m(\overline{AC})=6-2 = 4</m>. Then since segment <m>\overline{AB}</m>
            is the hypotenuse of the right triangle <m>\Delta ABC</m>, we can use 
            the Pythagorean Theorem to find its length, namely 
            <m>m(\overline{AB})=\sqrt{4^2+3^2}=\sqrt{9+16}=\sqrt{25}=5</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="diag-seg-measure">
            <caption>Measuring distance on a graph</caption>
            <image source="Pythmeasure.png">
                <shortdescription>Right triange ABC described above.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>
    <!--</sidebyside>-->
    </introduction>    
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-scaling-Cartesian">
        <title>Dilating Figures on a Cartesian <m>x,y</m>-Graph</title>
        <exploration xml:id="explor-magnify-quad">
            <task>
                <title>Constructing a Dilated Quadrilateral</title>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The following tasks refer to <xref ref="fig-scale-quad"/>:
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Compute the lengths of each segment using the Pythagorean
                                    Theorem:
                                    <ol>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{AB}</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{BC}</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{CD}</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{AD}</m>
                                        </li>
                                    </ol>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Use either a protractor or GeoGebra tools to measure the 
                                    angles:
                                    <ol>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\angle ABC</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\angle BCD</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\angle CDA</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\angle DAB</m>
                                        </li>
                                    </ol>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Multiply the coordinates of each vertex by
                                    2 to obtain coordinates for points <m>A'</m>, 
                                    <m>B'</m>, <m>C'</m>, and <m>D'</m>.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Then plot and connect the points to form quadrilateral
                                    <m>A'B'C'D'</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                    <!--Should I switch this back to an image?-->
                    <figure xml:id="fig-scale-quad">
                        <caption>GeoGebra app to scale a quadrilateral</caption>
                        <interactive xml:id="scale-quad-app"
                        platform="geogebra">
                        <slate surface="geogebra" material="njv9uaug"/>
                      </interactive>
                    </figure>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <title>Relationships between the Image and the Original</title>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Refer to your work in <xref ref="fig-scale-quad"/> as you 
                        answer the following:
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Describe how the quadrilateral <m>A'B'C'D'</m>you drew in
                                    <xref ref="fig-scale-quad"/> relates to the original 
                                    quadrilateral <m>ABCD</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Measure the new angles, <m>\angle A'B'C'</m>,
                                    <m>\angle B'C'D'</m>, <m>\angle C'D'A'</m>,
                                    and <m>D'A'B'</m>. How do they compare to the 
                                    original four angles?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Compute the lengths of the following segments
                                    <ol>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{A'B'}</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{B'C'}</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{C'D'}</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{A'D'}</m>
                                        </li>
                                    </ol>
                                    Compare these to the original side lengths.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Let <m>O</m> be the point <m>(0,0)</m>. 
                                    Draw the rays <m>\overrightarrow{OA'}</m>,
                                    <m>\overrightarrow{OB'}</m>, <m>\overrightarrow{OC'}</m>,
                                    and <m>\overrightarrow{OD'}</m>. What do you notice about 
                                    these rays?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>  
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
        </exploration>
    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-dilation-terminology">
        <title>Defining Dilation</title>
        <p>
            Quadrilateral <m>A'B'C'D'</m> created in <xref ref="fig-scale-quad"/> 
            is said to be the <term>image</term>
            of quadrilateral <m>ABCD</m> under the <term>dilation</term> with 
            <term>center</term> <m>(0,0)</m> and <term>scale factor</term> 2. Although
            the word dilation suggests enlarging, a dilation may either scale up or down.  
        </p>
        <exercise>
            <title>Did you notice?</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A few properties related to dilations appeared in 
                    <xref ref="explor-magnify-quad"/>. Answer the following:
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Does a dilation preserve the shape of figures?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Does a dilation preserve the size of figures?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                What does the scale factor tell you about the 
                                relationship between the lengths of segments in 
                                the dilated image compared to the lengths of segments
                                in the original figure?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                If <m>P</m> is a point and <m>P'</m> is its image under 
                                a dilation, what other point must lie on line 
                                <m>\overleftrightarrow{PP'}</m> ?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                What is the image of quadrilateral <m>A'B'C'D'</m>,
                                created in <xref ref="explor-magnify-quad"/> under the
                                dilation with center <m>(0,0)</m> and scale factor <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Dilations preserve shape but not size. The length of a dilated
                    image of a segment is <m>k</m> times the length of the original. 
                    The line <m>\overleftrightarrow{PP'}</m> must pass through the 
                    center of the dilation.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <definition xml:id="def-dilation">
            <idx><h>dilation</h></idx>
            <idx><h>similarity</h></idx>
            <idx><h>scale factor</h></idx>
            <idx><h>center</h><h>dilation</h></idx>
            <idx><h>magnification</h></idx>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A <term>dilation</term> with 
                    <term>center</term> <m>Q</m> and <term>scale factor</term> <m>k</m>
                    is a geometrical transformation that maps each point <m>P</m> to a point <m>P'</m>
                    on line <m>\overleftrightarrow{QP}</m> so that 
                    <m>m(\overline{QP'})=k\cdot m(\overline{QP})</m>. Point <m>P'</m> is
                    called the <term>image</term> of <m>P</m> under the dilation. 
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
    
        <exploration>
            <title>A Dilation not centered at the Origin</title>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    The center of a dilation does not have to be the origin,
                    <m>(0,0)</m>. It could be any point in the plane.
                </p>
            </introduction>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Use a print copy or the Geogebra applet of 
                        <xref ref="fig-GGapp-new-center"/> to complete the following:
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Sketch or construct the dilation of triangle <m>\Delta EFG</m>
                                    with center <m>H</m> and scale factor <m>3</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Sketch or construct the dilation of triangle <m>\Delta EFG</m>
                                    with center <m>H</m> and scale factor <m>\frac{3}{2}</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Sketch or construct the dilation of triangle <m>\Delta EFG</m>
                                    with center <m>H</m> and scale factor <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-GGapp-new-center">
                        <caption>GeoGebra applet for dilating triangle <m>\Delta EFG</m></caption>
                        <interactive xml:id="scale-not-origin"
                        platform="geogebra">
                        <slate surface="geogebra" material="uwqquwpn"/>
                      </interactive>
                    </figure>
                </statement>
            </task>
        </exploration>
</subsection>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-dilate-similartri-example">
    <title>Dilation and Proportion</title>
    <exploration xml:id="explor-nested-simtri">
        <title>Recognizing a Dilation</title>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                In <xref ref="fig-nested-simtri"/>, a dilation takes 
                <m>\angle ABC</m> to <m>\angle DEC</m>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What is the center of the dilation?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What is the scale factor of this dilation? 
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Compute each of the ratios:
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <m>\frac{DE}{AB}</m>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <m>\frac{EC}{BC}</m>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <m>\frac{CD}{CA}</m>
                        </li> 
                    </ol>
                    What do you notice?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Compute the ratios:
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <m>\frac{DE}{BC}</m>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <m>\frac{EC}{AC}</m>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <m>\frac{CD}{AB}</m>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                    Are these the same? Why or why not?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Are any of the angles in triangle <m>\Delta ABC</m> congruent 
                    to an angle in <m>\Delta DEC</m>? Identify all pairs of congruent
                    angles.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Recall that two triangles <m>\Delta ABC</m> and <m>\Delta DEF</m> 
                    are said to be congruent if the two triangles have three pairs of 
                    congruent corresponding angles, namely <m>\angle ABC\cong \angle DEF</m>,
                    <m>\angle BCA\cong \angle EFD</m>, and <m>\angle CAB\cong \angle FDE</m>, 
                    and three pairs of congruent corresponding sides, namely <m>AB=DE</m>,
                    <m>BC=EF</m>, and <m>CA=FD</m>. Are triangles <m>\Delta ABC</m> and 
                    <m>\Delta DEC</m> in <xref ref="fig-nested-simtri"/> congruent? Explain.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="task-explor-nested-simtri-defsimilar">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Two triangles <m>\Delta ABC</m> and <m>\Delta DEF</m> are 
                    said to be <xref ref="def-similar" text="custom">similar</xref> triangles
                    if the two triangles have three pairs of congruent corresponding 
                    angles and the ratios of each of the three pairs of corresponding 
                    sides are equal; i.e., <m>\angle A\cong \angle D</m>, 
                    <m>\angle B\cong \angle E</m>, <m>\angle C\cong \angle F</m>, and
                    <m>\frac{DE}{AB}=\frac{EF}{BC}=\frac{FD}{CA}</m>.
                    Are the triangles in <xref ref="fig-nested-simtri"/> similar? Explain..
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exploration>
    <figure xml:id="fig-nested-simtri">
        <caption>GeoGebra applet for <xref ref="explor-nested-simtri"/></caption>
        <interactive xml:id="GGapp-nested-simtri"
                    platform="geogebra">
                    <slate surface="geogebra" material="enwtc22h"/>
                  </interactive>
    </figure>
    
</subsection>
